cat:
NAME
	cat - concatenate file to standard output

SYNOPSIS
	cat [OPTION] [FILE]

DESCRIPTION
	Concatenates and prints the FILE to standard output.

	-n, --number
		number all output lines

EXAMPLES
	cat file_1
		Output file_1's contents to standard output.

	cat -n file_1
		Output all file_1's lines numbered.
cd:
NAME
	cd - change current working directory

SYNOPSIS
	cd [DIRECTORY]

DESCRIPTION
	Moves inside DIRECTORY.

EXAMPLES
	cd dir_1
		Move inside dir_1 subdirectory.

	cd dir_1/dir_2/dir_3
		Move inside dir_3 subdirectory from the current directory,
		dir_1 and dir_2 being in between.

	cd, cd ~
		Change directory to the home directory.

	cd ..
		Move to the parent directory of the current directory.
clear:
NAME
	clear - clear the terminal screen

SYNOPSIS
	clear

DESCRIPTION
	Clears the terminal screen writing to the standard output.
date:
NAME
	date - print the system date and time

SYNOPSIS
	date

DESCRIPTION
	Displays the current date and time.
edit:
NAME
	edit - edit plain text

SYNOPSIS
	edit [FILE]

DESCRIPTION
	Opens FILE in a text editor.
	It can be used to edit all kinds of plain text.

EXAMPLES
	edit file_1
		Open file_1 in a text editor.
exit:
NAME
	exit - cause normal process termination

SYNOPSIS
	exit

DESCRIPTION
	Causes normal process termination and closes the terminal.
help:
NAME
	help - print all built-in commands

SYNOPSIS
	help

DESCRIPTION
	Displays a list of all integrated shell commands.
history:
NAME
	history - print previous commands

SYNOPSIS
	history

DESCRIPTION
	Displays a numbered list of previous commands.
ls:
NAME
	ls - list directory contents

SYNOPSIS
	ls [OPTION] [DIRECTORY]

DESCRIPTION
	Lists DIRECTORY's children (the current directory by default).

	-a, --all
		do not ignore entries starting with .

EXAMPLES
	ls
		List current directory contents.

	ls -a dir_1
		List dir_1 subdirectory contents, including hidden files.
man:
NAME
	man - an interface to the system reference manuals

SYNOPSIS
	man [ENTRY]

DESCRIPTION
	Displays the manual entry for ENTRY.

EXAMPLES
	man ls
		Display the manual entry for the item (program) ls.
mkdir:
NAME
	mkdir - make directories

SYNOPSIS
	mkdir [DIRECTORY]

DESCRIPTION
	Creates the DIRECTORY, if it does not already exist.

EXAMPLES
	mkdir dir_1
		Create dir_1 as a subdirectory of the current directory.

	mkdir dir_1/dir_2
		Create dir_2 as a subdirectory of dir_1.
mv:
NAME
	mv - move (rename) files

SYNOPSIS
	mv [SOURCE] [DEST]

DESCRIPTION
	Renames SOURCE to DEST, or moves SOURCE to DEST.

EXAMPLES
	mv file_1 file_2
		Rename file_1 to file_2.

	mv file_1 dir_1
		Move file_1 from current directory to dir_1 subdirectory.
pwd:
NAME
	pwd - print name of current/working directory

SYNOPSIS
	pwd

DESCRIPTION
	Prints the full filename of the current working directory.
rm:
NAME
	rm - remove files or directories

SYNOPSIS
	rm [OPTION] [FILE]

DESCRIPTION
	Removes the FILE. By default, it does not remove directories.

	-r, -R, --recursive
		remove directories and their contents recursively

EXAMPLES
	rm file_1
		Remove file_1.

	rm -r dir_1
		Remove the dir_1 subdirectory and its children recursively.
rmdir:
NAME
	rmdir - remove empty directories

SYNOPSIS
	rmdir [DIRECTORY]

DESCRIPTION
	Removes the DIRECTORY, if it is empty.

EXAMPLES
	rmdir dir_1
		Remove the dir_1 subdirectory.

	rmdir dir_1/dir_2
		Remove the dir_2 subdirectory from dir_1.
touch:
NAME
	touch - change file timestamps

SYNOPSIS
	touch [FILE]

DESCRIPTION
	Creates the FILE, if it does not already exist.

EXAMPLES
	touch file_1
		Create file_1 in the current directory.

	touch dir_1/file_1
		Create file_1 inside the dir_1 subdirectory.
